<HEAD>Episcopal Clergy Convene To Establish Traditionalists Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> bishop has called for recognition of a `` church within a church'' as a haven for conservative Episcopalians opposed to such so-called liberal trends as the ordination of women. `` Let us firmly declare and commit ourselves to the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> and to the provinces of the <ORGANIZATION> Anglican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communion </ORGANIZATION> that it is our will to be the church within the church,'' the Rt. Rev. <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, said Thursday. <PERSON> Pope </PERSON>, bishop of the Diocese of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> and president of the Evangelical and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION>, addressed nearly 1,200 delegates at the opening session of the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Synod </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> on Thursday. <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> is president of the Evangelical and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION>, and he and other bishops in the mission called the synod last year after the Rev. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> was consecrated as the first female bishop in the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. The bishops called Ms. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>' election `` the final crisis.'' <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> and other speakers contended that segments of the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> are abandoning the biblical faith through decisions to ordain female priests and bishops and efforts to relax moral teachings on sexuality and marriage. `` We must do all we can to remain within this church and do all we can to transform this church,'' said the Rt. Rev. <PERSON> John-David </PERSON> <PERSON> Schofield </PERSON> of the Diocese of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joachin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fresno </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` If it will not be permitted, then we will have to take the next step when it comes.'' <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s laws do not prevent the traditionalists from forming a voluntary association, and he called for the acceptance of the new organization as a way for traditionalists to stay within the church. `` We seek nothing more and nothing less than to provide a way to maintain and propagate the gospel of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> through the unchanged tradition of the historic church. ... Society, we believe, is hungry for this kind of church and gospel _ neither of which is subject to the shifting sands of this present age,'' <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Pope </PERSON>'s proposal would create a voluntary organization that would allow traditionalist bishops and priests to visit parishes. Traditionalist bishops, a small minority in the 2.9 million-member <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, say the church has lost 1 million members in the past two decades because of liberal changes, including the ordination of women.
