<SECOND>AM-Stringfellow Toxics,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury: California Must Share Cost of Stringfellow Cleanup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> should share the huge cost of cleaning up the Stringfellow toxic waste site, a project with a potential price tag of up to $ 740 million, a jury decided Friday. The six-member federal jury did not determine how much the state should contribute to the cleanup of the <LOCATION> Riverside </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> hazardous waste site, leaving that decision to <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ideman </PERSON>. The decision came after less than a day of deliberations. The Stringfellow site opened in 1956 and received an estimated 34 million gallons of acids, pesticides and other toxic materials before it was closed in 1972. The panel ruled the state was liable because it supervised construction of the toxic landfill, delayed cleanup activities and allowed a dangerous condition to exist on public property. The jurors also found the state liable for maintaining a nuisance and breaching its duty to deal with toxic contamination, but ruled the state was not negligent in choosing or designing the site in the early 1950s, or for failing to remedy the toxic contamination. The decision pleased lawyers for <PERSON> J.B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stringfellow </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, owner of the quarry that contained the dump and 14 users of the landfill who were all found liable to share cleanup costs by <PERSON> Ideman </PERSON>. `` We believe the implications of today's ruling is that the state will bear the lion's share,'' said attorney <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON>. <PERSON> Stringfellow </PERSON>, 62, of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION> said he was delighted with the jury's decision. `` I feel better,'' he said. `` It's the first time anyone had heard my story.'' Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said the verdict favored the state because it rejected the plaintiffs' claims the state was negligent in choosing and designing the dumpsite, and that it allegedly failed to remedy problems that became apparent in the 1970s. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> hinted that an appeal was possible, saying that he felt the jury would not have found the state liable at all if retired judge <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Peetris </PERSON>, who presided over the fact-finding hearing, had not refused to instruct the jury on several legal defenses possibly applicable to the state. `` It is the opinion of the attorney general's office that these defenses would have barred any finding of liability against the state on the portion of the verdict that dealt with those theories,'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said. During the two-month proceeding, Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Noble </PERSON> told the jury operators of the Stringfellow site were to blame because they allegedly failed to follow design specifications in a key area of the dump site. The alleged error allowed toxic materials to overflow barriers and spread into groundwater supplies, she said. Stringfellow attorney <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Bisgaard </PERSON> said his client initially balked at the idea of putting the toxic dump on his property but relented after state officials allegedly promised to help build and operate the dump. <PERSON> Bisgaard </PERSON> said state geologists erroneously determined in 1955 that the quarry was located above an impermeable granite bedrock suitable for safe dumping. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goode </PERSON>, attorney for <ORGANIZATION> Rohr </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, one of the companies that dumped chemicals at the Stringfellow site, said the jury decision shifted blame from companies that merely accepted state assurances the site was safe. `` We were found liable without having done anything wrong,'' <PERSON> Goode </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
