<HEAD>Jury Hears Cockpit Tape of Final Moments Before Fatal Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An audio tape played in a courtroom Friday featured a copilot saying `` That's a gun,'' following the sounds of shots fired aboard a commuter jetliner that crashed in 1987, killing all 43 people aboard. Jurors heard the pilot and copilot groan loudly after apparent gunfire in the final moments preceding the crash of the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> flight blamed on a gun-toting former airline employee bent on revenge after he was fired for on-the-job theft. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, 35, of <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> is alleged to have smuggled a .44 - caliber Magnum aboard Flight 1771 on Dec. 7, 1987 by flashing his employee badge at a security gate and bypassing metal Relatives of eight passengers and two crew members are suing <ORGANIZATION> PSA </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airports </ORGANIZATION> and a security company, contending they were negligent in allowing <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> to board the jet bound for <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> with a loaded gun. The airline, airport agency and <ORGANIZATION> Ogden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> contend <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> was solely responsible for the fatal crash. <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> was an employee of <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>, the parent company of <ORGANIZATION> PSA </ORGANIZATION>, until he was fired by a man he allegedly shot in the passenger section of the plane before he entered the cockpit and fired on the flight crew. <PERSON> Julian </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a pilot and former air traffic controller, testified as an expert witness for the plaintiffs using a recording of the cockpit crew's conversation with an air traffic controller in <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION>. The tape began with the sound of a possible gunshot. Pilot: `` My God!'' -LRB- Sound of second shot. -RRB- Copilot: `` That's a gun.'' Pilot: `` Yeah, I know. Tell'em we got a problem.'' Copilot: -LRB- Sending distress signal. -RRB- Unknown crew member: `` We've got a problem. We've had a gun fired. Are they on board the aircraft?'' Air Controller: `` I beg your pardon.'' Crew member: `` ... and we've had a gun fired on board the aircraft.'' Air Controller: `` OK. Do you want to go to <LOCATION> Monterey </LOCATION> Can you make it, sir?'' -LRB- Sound of door opening. -RRB- Unknown female: `` Hi, Captain.'' Pilot: `` What kind of problem ...'' -LRB- Loud crashing noise. -RRB- Pilot and copilot: `` Ohh.'' -LRB- Loud groan. -RRB- -LRB- Tinkle of breaking glass. Soft banging sound, possibly of the cockpit door banging shut. -RRB- The plane crashed minutes later in central <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> Special Agent <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Varley </PERSON> told the jury a .44 - caliber pistol with six spent cartridges was found in the It was traced to an <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION> man who said he loaned it to <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>. <PERSON> Varley </PERSON> said a note _ in <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>'s handwriting and addressed to his former supervisor _ was found that read: `` I think it's sort of ironical we end up like this. I asked for some leniency for my family ... Well, I got none and you'll get none.'' <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Wecht </PERSON>, attorney for the plaintiffs, said <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> bought about $ 350,000 in flight insurance from a terminal vending machine before boarding the airliner.
