<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While some city slickers may think real cowboys are an endangered species, cowboy poets know better. Sixteen cowboy poets participated in Friday's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cowboy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symposium </ORGANIZATION> and Celebration, reciting verses about bull riding, the cowboy's changing way of life and the barren land they try to tame. `` As long as there are cows and people eat hamburgers, there will be cowboys and my audience will exist,'' said <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON>, who quit his work as a cattleman and veterinarian in the early 1980s to become a full-time cowboy poet. The poems were melancholy and humorous; <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Underwood </PERSON>'s had plenty of whimsy. One verse was about a dream of a scientifically enhanced steer with `` eyes a big a truck headlights, each horn weighed a thousand pounds.'' `` Cowboy poetry is looking at our flaws and foible and laughing at ourselves,'' said <PERSON> Black </PERSON>. `` I try to nudge that fine line between good taste and throwing up in your hat.'' Black recites his poems, which run as long as 10 minutes, from memory almost effortlessly. However, on a recent appearance on the <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> show, he was so nervous he considered using a TelePrompTer. `` But I decided, no, that's not the cowboy way,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SPRINGDALE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Popeye </PERSON> will soon return to his watch outside a spinach warehouse. Pranksters stole the 7-foot, 200-pound fiberglass statue last month, but an anonymous tip a few days later led police to <PERSON> Popeye </PERSON>. He was in a ditch. A note, stuck in the sailor's mouth, said: `` We deeply regret the absence of your friend <PERSON> Popeye </PERSON>. We are returning him because he just did n't seem happy with us. He would n't eat his spinich -LRB- sic -RRB- so we figured something was wrong. Help <PERSON> Popeye </PERSON> find his real home.'' The note was signed by a fraternity from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION>, but <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said he doubts that the fraternity took <PERSON> Popeye </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Allen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has since repainted the statue. The company also is working on a way to re-erect the monument to spinach vitality `` that we think will be pretty secure,'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, spokesman for the family-owned business, said Friday. He said the company is n't looking for the Popeye thieves. `` We're just glad to have <PERSON> Popeye </PERSON> back in the family,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With one flush, <PERSON> Trish </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> saw her wedding go down the toilet. A day before she was to tie the knot, the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION> woman accidentally flushed a $ 5,000 engagement ring down her toilet. <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION>, preoccupied with prewedding arrangements, forgot she had wrapped the ring in toilet paper to protect it. After she wiped the sink dry with some other toilet paper, she flushed the whole clump. `` I just about hyperventilated on the floor. I said, ` This is the beginning of the end of my marriage.''' Enter a team of Roto-Rooter employees. The workers tore up the front lawn, built a special dam and flushed gallons of water into a sewer main. And they found it. `` I gave them all the champagne out of my refrigerator,'' said <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION>, a 27-year-old flight attendant. `` I was just passing it out in the street.'' `` It was a real long shot,'' said <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Williamson </PERSON>, a Roto-Rooter employee. `` I did n't think myself that we'd ever get it.'' <PERSON> Trish </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> were married on schedule, May 20.
