<HEAD>Artist Erte Sells Works In Atlantic City Casino</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Noted artist <PERSON> Erte </PERSON> will collect big money in <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, but not by gambling. `` I am bored by gambling,'' the master of art deco design said. Instead, <PERSON> Erte </PERSON> will exhibit and sell some of his private collection in a casino ballroom tonight. In his suite at <ORGANIZATION> Trump </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Castle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> and Casino this week, the 96-year-old artist was signing special exhibit books for high rollers who are invited to see and bid on Erte's special exhibit. On Sunday, the exhibit will be open to the public and available for purchase. The collection includes 50 original watercolors, some up to 80 years old. It will also feature some of Erte's distinctive sculptures and jewelry and a costume recently designed by the artist for the new Broadway musical `` Stardust.'' Born <PERSON> Romain </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Tirtoff </PERSON>, the artist took the name Erte from his initials. Today, the tiny white-haired man, who designs his own suits and chunky jewelry, smiled when asked if he has any favorites among his pieces. `` They are all my children and I am their father,'' he said. But he admitted to some affection for one abstract sculpture in his <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> flat, titled `` Autumn.'' `` I will never give it away because it is the center of my decorations,'' he said. The artist said he has created almost 20,000 designs, mostly of women bedecked in elaborate outfits. And Erte's mind and paintbrushes keep flowing. `` Retirement is to die, and I do n't want to die,'' he said. `` I will retire when I die.'' Erte, who is building a new home in <LOCATION> Majorca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, has spent most of his years in a <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> apartment, said <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Estorick </PERSON>, managing director of the <LOCATION> Grosvenor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gallery </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Erte </PERSON>'s exclusive world agent `` There have been five different owners of his flat who spent years waiting for him to die,'' <PERSON> Estorick </PERSON> said, chuckling. <PERSON> Erte </PERSON> keeps living a full life, traveling around the world to exhibits and designing costumes and scenery for upcoming theater productions. `` I always make the complete package for a show,'' he said. `` I hate to make costumes for someone else's setting. If one painter makes the background and one the costumes, it's not art, it's an accommodation.'' The end results are richly colored costumes and headpieces melding with spectacular background effects. <PERSON> Erte </PERSON> said he first started drawing at age 3. At 6, he drew an evening dress that his mother later had a dressmaker copy for her to wear. Years later, from 1915 to 1937, he created covers and illustrations for <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>'s Bazaar. He never married, yet he has created thousands of dreamlike images of women, with inspiration that he said comes from heaven. <PERSON> Estorick </PERSON> said <PERSON> Erte </PERSON> `` is not only a meticulous creator, but unlike fashion designers, he is a basic designer and an artist. Other designers have to bring in artists to flesh out their ideas.'' Even with `` the foibles of old age _ rheumatic problems and old teeth _ the fact is that <PERSON> Erte </PERSON> is a discipline machine. He always is a no-nonsense, hard-working artist,'' <PERSON> Estorick </PERSON> said.
