<HEAD>USDA Allows Haying, Grazing on Conservation Set-Aside Land</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is opening up millions of acres of erosion-prone land for hay cutting and livestock grazing to help farmers in drought-stricken areas. <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> announced the assistance on Friday, saying producers in more than 500 counties in 16 states currently could be eligible. `` Livestock producers have exhausted stocks of hay that were carried into winter, and they are now faced with another dry spring,'' Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said. `` So they're out of hay and short of grass. The land being made available is part of a conservation reserve program that pays people to take their most erosion-prone land out of production for at least 10 years and improve it by planting grasses and trees. The haying assistance would be authorized county by county in states where a livestock emergency has been declared, currently 16 states, mostly in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, according to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>. Tighter restrictions would be placed on livestock grazing on the so-called CRP acres. It would be allowed only after a visual inspection of the land by the <ORGANIZATION> Soil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to ensure it would not suffer any damage. The 16 states are: <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. County offices of the <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stabilization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> must seek authority for the haying and grazing privileges. <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> <PERSON> Shipp </PERSON>, <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>'s press secretary, said about 570 counties in the 16 states were eligible currently to apply for the CRP-related assistance because they had received livestock emergency declarations. Additional counties and states could become eligible later. As of last year, 28 million acres nationwide _ 19 million of those in the 16 states _ had been enrolled in the conservation reserve program, which was established by the 1985 farm law as a way to reduce erosion and trim overproduction on marginal land. The government paid $ 1.4 billion in yearly rental payments to producers participating in the program. Friday's announcement is the latest federal aid made available to farmers facing crop and livestock losses from lingering drought conditions. It followed <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>'s visit to <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> earlier this week and earlier visits to <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> last month authorized livestock grazing and hay cutting on land taken out of production under this year's commodity programs, but put off a decision on conservation reserve acreage. In addition, livestock and poultry producers have been allowed to buy surplus government-owned grain at discount prices. These restrictions will apply to the <ORGANIZATION> CRP </ORGANIZATION> assistance: _ Rental payments to producers next year will be cut 50 percent for those who cut hay or graze livestock Nationwide, annual payments averaged $ 48 an acre last year. _ No <ORGANIZATION> CRP </ORGANIZATION> land with grasses planted after July 1, 1987, will be eligible _ Only one hay cutting will be allowed, and none permitted after July 15 At least three inches of stubble must be left, and a one-fourth of each field must be left untouched to provide cover for wildlife. _ Local <ORGANIZATION> ASCS </ORGANIZATION> operations will determine how long grazing will be permitted on <ORGANIZATION> CRP </ORGANIZATION> land as well as the number of livestock No grazing will be allowed after Aug. 1.
</TEXT>
