<HEAD>S&amp;L Capital Requirements to Rise, But Rules Likely to Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Most savings and loan associations will have to increase the amount of capital they keep in reserve, the government says. The increase is required by current regulations that tie the capital standards to the industry's annual profitability. As a result, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that minimum requirements for most savings and loans will rise from the current 3.44 percent of liabilities to 3.75 percent at the start of next year. The regulations would gradually increase capital requirements to 6 percent. The rules, however, are likely to be superseded by legislation under consideration in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that would overhaul S & amp; L regulations and require thrift operators to put more of their own money at risk to stay in business. The tougher capital requirements proposed by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as part of his S & amp; L bailout package have been the subject of intense debate on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, with differences between <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> proposals likely to be ironed out by a joint conference committee. Under the changes announced Friday by the bank board, <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls in the standard group _ which includes healthy thrifts and covers about 80 percent of the industry _ would see their capital requirements rise to 3.60 percent on July 1 and to 3.75 percent next January. Capital requirements vary case by case for <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls in the lower group _ made up of thrifts experiencing financial difficulty or under federal supervision _ but their required capital would rise by 0.19 percent on July 1 and another 0.18 percent next January.
