<HEAD>Dispute With Bar Over Judicial Selection Settled, Thornburgh Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> says the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> may have too much influence in the selection of federal judges, a position that puts him in partial agreement with conservative critics. `` In some respects, the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>'s standing committee has become larger than life,'' <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> said Friday at a hearing of his committee. He was referring to the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>'s Standing Committee on Federal Judiciary. `` Surely the -LRB- Judiciary -RRB- committee has over the years, given the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> standing committee an exalted status,'' he said. But <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> also said that the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>'s opinion on judges was sought in the past because `` cronyism and not competence was all too often the reason for choosing a nominee.'' <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> spoke the same day that Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> told reporters he considered his dispute with the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> over judicial selection to be settled. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> told reporters he regarded an agreement reached with the bar group last month `` to be dispositive of this issue.'' Conservative senators have been smoldering ever since four of the standing committee's 15 members voted to find then-Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> unqualified for a seat on the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Joined by a number of other lawmakers, conservative senators have been calling for an overhaul or even an end to the process under which the committee meets behind closed doors and does not explain how it arrives at its conclusions or how the individual committee members voted. The system, Sen. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, `` is a moldering, corrupted, malodorous old relic which should be given a quick burial for the sake of public health.'' Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> it `` is no longer appropriate that this one private organization be granted a status not accorded to any other group.'' `` It exercises a virtual veto over judicial nominees,'' <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said. But Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, scoffed at what he called conservative concerns over the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>'s liberal focus. He said he had been an <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> member for decades and `` there's no question about it _ I would put the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> on the conservative side.'' `` Who are you kidding?'' <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> said. `` This is the hierarchy of all the big corporate law firms in the country.'' Under the new agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>, the group promised to drop a disputed paragraph from a brochure outlining its methods of reviewing potential nominees for the federal bench. The paragraph to be erased says: `` Political or ideological philosophy are not considered, except to the extent that they may bear upon other factors.'' Far from barring consideration of politics, critics say, the paragraph specifically opens the door to such inquiries. <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> officials also promised to refrain from weighing the ideology and political philosophy of potential candidates for judge whose names are sent to it for review by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>. The officials, however, made a point of adding they had never considered those factors in their evaluations. Names of potential federal judges are sent to the president by senators and other influential officials. Before they are nominated by the president, they are evaluated by the administration and investigated by the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. Since 1953, the government also has maintained an arrangement under which potential candidates are screened by the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>, the major professional association of the nation's lawyers, before the president sends their names to Capitol Hill for confirmation by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>.
