<HEAD>The Man `Poles Love to Hate' Running for Parliament</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 His television campaign ridicules his prominent ears as `` disquieting, even fatal.'' Known as the man Poles love to hate, polls show he is trailing his Solidarity-backed candidate by a 7-1 margin in the race for a seat in parliament in Sunday's balloting. He is <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON>, the loyal government spokesman for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s communist authorities since 1981 Urban was the point man for seven years in the government's campaign against the Solidarity union movement And he was among the first government officials to announce his candidacy in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s first democratic elections since World War II. In his usually provocative manner Urban, who is now information minister, is running as an independent. The Sejm, or parliament, has 460 seats and 161 are open to opposition candidates, including independents. The other seats are reserved for members of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and its allies. As government spokesman, Urban gave his first news conference in December 1981 on the day the government imposed martial law and suppressed Solidarity. The independent union movement subsequently was outlawed but was legalized again in April following negotiations that also set the framework for Sunday's elections. Over the years Urban belittled Solidarity founder <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> as the `` former head of a former union.'' Now he is running for a <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION> seat in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s center-city district against <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Lapicki </PERSON>, a Soviet-endorsed actor. Opposition polls show Urban to be a heavy underdog. But the results could be affected by the large number of ballots expected to be cast by Poles abroad. The district has about 140,000 eligible voters, but some 600,000 Poles abroad, including many embassy and government contract workers, also will have their ballots counted in the district. Urban was promoted to information minister on April 17, the day Solidarity became legal again. As government spokesman he conducted weekly news conference that were televised and gave him a national audience. He frequently would mention polling data showing more than half of the population disapproved of him, but his news conferences were the highest rated weekly show on television. In the first few days of the campaign the opposition newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Gazeta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wyborcza </ORGANIZATION> had so many articles concerning Urban that one letter writer told the editors to avoid `` Urbanophobia.'' <PERSON> Ryszard </PERSON> <PERSON> Straus </PERSON>, an Urban aide, said of the polls: `` Urban is in a better situation than other candidates because he is a well-known person and does not have to introduce himself to the public like the others, so it is a big advantage. Ninety-six percent of people questioned said they knew who Urban was.'' Urban is a journalist and satirist who was associated with Prime Minister <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> weekly Polityka. He mocks his distinctive appearance _ a small man with a circular bald pate and large ears. In a program on state television, controlled by Urban as information minister, a singer sang, `` Strange ears had he, strange hears had he,'' while Urban was shown as a child, teen-ager and young man. Video-writing drew circles around his ears to make them look even larger. In a country where many politicians are rigid and humorless, Urban recently told a campaign rally, `` Everyone knows who I am.''
