<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Glance     06-03 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Glance,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Look at Poland Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are facts and figures on <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s parliamentary and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> elections Sunday:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 WHAT'S AT STAKE _ Of 460 seats in the Sejm, or parliament, 161 _ or 35 percent _ are open to opposition candidates. The remaining 299 are set aside for members of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> or its allies. All the seats are contested, except for a `` national list'' of 35 positions for which the communist coalition selected unopposed candidates. There are 1,745 candidates nationwide for the 425 contested seats. In the newly created <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, all 100 seats are freely contested, making it the first fully democratically picked legislative chamber in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc. There are 553 candidates nationwide for those seats.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 VOTING _ The polls will be open from 6 a.m. to 10 p.m. There will be 22,411 polling places in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and about 205 abroad, mainly at Polish diplomatic posts and construction projects. There are 27,211,188 eligible voters, according to the government. Voters must be 18. If they live abroad, they must provide proof of Polish citizenship. Voters cast ballots by crossing out all names on the ballot except that of the chosen candidate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 VICTORY MARGIN _ Candidates must receive more than half of the votes. If none does, the two candidates receiving the most ballots will participate in run-off elections June 18. The candidates on the `` national list'' in the uncontested races also must receive more than 50 percent of the votes. If they do not, the seat will not be filled.
</TEXT>
