<SECOND>PM-Third World Books, Bjt,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mississippi Group Funnels Millions of Books to Third World Countries</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON> finds it altogether fitting to be shipping millions of books each year from <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, the state with the highest illiteracy rate, to countries where books are a scarce commodity. Starting with a single shipment to <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION> in 1983, <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON> has sent more than 2 million books to countries in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Her non-profit company, <ORGANIZATION> Books </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION>, which has won <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> praise, operates from <LOCATION> Yazoo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, a small town 40 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> in the impoverished <LOCATION> Delta </LOCATION> area where she grew up. `` <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> seems an unlikely place for the exportation of books,'' <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON> said, echoing comments she has heard time and again from book publishers, whom she approaches for donations, and from foreign embassies she contacts to determine which books are needed. The statement does n't bother her. `` It makes me feel special if I can dismantle stereotypes _ again,'' said <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON>, a black woman. <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON>, who obtained her doctorate in music at <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, had completed a two-year education program at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> in 1983 when she was approached by <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, the late founder of Books for the World. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, the president of <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, tapped <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON> to take over the agency. Former President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> has become the agency's honorary board chairman. An estimated 27 percent of adult Mississippians are functionally illiterate, the highest rate in the nation, and its school dropout rate is also among the highest. But in many Third World countries, even the literate often ca n't read. `` If there are people in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> who do n't have books, it's not because books are n't available It's a social problem,'' <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON> said. At <LOCATION> Monrovia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> College </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION>, where she visited in 1983, <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON> met students `` who had been to college, but had never had books they could take home and read.'' Sometimes a single textbook must serve a classroom full of students. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, leery of publishers who dump books in the Third World to turn print overruns into tax deductions, has helped <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON> work in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` We felt there was a great need in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the initial shipments were very popular,'' said <PERSON> Allison </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON>, deputy assistant secretary of state for <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> affairs. Books for the World asks foreign educators what kinds of books they need, then sends a sample copy of every title before shipping tons of books that are n't wanted, <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON> will take a two-week tour of 18 African countries beginning June 15, and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassies in those countries have helped her make appointments with potential recipients. <PERSON> Ricks </PERSON> said her office operates on a shoestring. Textbook publishers are approached for donations; corporations moving large shipments of merchandise are asked to slip in a load of books. Charitable groups such as the <ORGANIZATION> YMCA </ORGANIZATION> and World Vision that operate in the targeted countries help in distribution. Her office includes another full-time staffer and volunteers from a prison work-release program. <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, education coordinator for the <ORGANIZATION> Carter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Uganda </LOCATION> last summer and wanted to find out how the center could ease the severe book shortage there. `` We made many, many phone calls to people to try to find out how to do this, find out about the problems we might encounter,'' <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> said. `` We found out Books for the World has already put this into motion and has done very well with it.''
