<SECOND>PM-Alar, Bjt,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alar Sales in United States Halted by Manufacturer; Move Draws Praise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The voluntary decision by <ORGANIZATION> Alar </ORGANIZATION>'s manufacturer to take the chemical off the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market drew praise from the nation's apple belt as the best way to win back consumers <ORGANIZATION> Uniroyal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> continued to defend the chemical as safe, but said Friday that continued use on apples raised public doubts about the safety of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s food supply. The chemical has been labeled a possible carcinogen, although tests are continuing. `` We should be hopeful and expect this will be the beginning of restoring consumer confidence,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McAlister </PERSON>, a spokesman for Selah-based <ORGANIZATION> Tree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Top </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest apple juice maker. But other industry figures said the action is unlikely to help the current crop, which has turned into a financial disaster. Prices have fallen 40 percent, to below the cost of production, and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state has 3.3 million more boxes of apples in storage than at this time last year. That includes an unknown quantity of Alar-treated apples that may have to be dumped. `` It wo n't make any difference for this year, but it certainly should help us as far as sales for next year's crop,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> DeWitt </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Wenatchee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which charts apple sales. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state produces about half the nation's apples and has about 12 million of the 42-pound boxes in storage. Apple growers and processors nationwide had pleaded with Uniroyal to withdraw Alar. Public fears had cost each group an estimated $ 100 million in sales so far this year, industry groups estimate. The voluntary withdrawal by <ORGANIZATION> Uniroyal </ORGANIZATION>, which is based in <LOCATION> Middlebury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, means consumers will be guaranteed that this fall's apple crop will be Alar-free, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> State <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Sales of daminozide, which is sold under the name Alar, would continue to about 70 foreign markets, including some that export apples and apple products to this country, <ORGANIZATION> Uniroyal </ORGANIZATION> said. Supplies of the chemical held by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> customers may be returned for refunds, the company said. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said late Friday it has reached agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Uniroyal </ORGANIZATION> on a plan to monitor the removal of Alar from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market, although it is still legal to use. The agency also said it will notify foreign governments about agency concerns about Alar. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has said it plans to ban use of daminozide in food products because tests in laboratory animals have linked a byproduct of Alar with cancer after the chemical is heated. Final action on the proposed regulation is not expected until late 1990. Uniroyal has disputed the findings and company Vice President <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Wylie </PERSON> said Friday: `` We want to emphasize that we have not changed our opinion about the safety of daminozide.'' The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> estimates that from 5 percent to 15 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> apple crop is treated with Alar, a growth regulator that improves the apple's appearance and gives it a longer shelf life. The Alar issue was ignited by the private <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>'s report that concluded that eating Alar-treated apples increased cancer risk, especially in children. The findings have been disputed by the apple industry and several federal agencies, including <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>, declared apples safe to eat.
