<SECOND>PM-New Bridge, Bjt,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Expensive Freeway Segment Ever Built Opens</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SE1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With much fanfare, authorities Sunday are opening a seven-mile stretch of Interstate 90 that has the dubious distinction of being the most expensive segment of freeway ever built. It is part of a $ 1.46 billion highway project for the mushrooming <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> metropolis to build roads that probably will be badly congested by the time they are completed in 1994. For the time being, the new link between <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bellevue </LOCATION> across <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> brings welcome relief from the twice-daily creep across the lake's two existing four-lane spans that become jammed by fender-benders. Commuters also say goodbye to an infamous I-90 lane that switched direction depending on the commute. With no barrier to separate traffic, motorists tagged it the `` death lane.'' The completed segment includes a floating bridge, a triple-decker tunnel with one level for bicycles and pedestrians, and a concrete-slab roof over sections of the highway that will be landscaped as parks. The freeway, proposed in 1957, drew the wrath of residents, who wanted to protect neighborhoods, and of environmentalists. In 1971, planners agreed to scale back the project and build tunnels on the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> side of the lake, but an environmental impact statement was n't approved until 1979. By then, federal money had dried up, and it was n't until <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> raised the gas tax in 1982 that funds became available. Construction began in earnest the next year. So far, $ 860 million has been spent. The balance of the money will go to reopening and linking up one of the old bridges, located to the south of the new structure, as well as other additions. At about $ 200 million a mile, the freeway has set a record for costliness, but one that will soon fall to a project at I-90's other terminus _ <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, according to <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> project manager <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Henkel </PERSON> That $ 4.4 billion project will rebuild <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> 93 through downtown <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and construct a third harbor tunnel to link I-90 with <LOCATION> Logan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. Despite `` a major crisis every second day,'' <ORGANIZATION> Henkel </ORGANIZATION> said, he is on time and $ 16 million under budget. The project includes the world's largest soft-ground tunnel _ 1,500 feet long and 63 feet in diameter _ <ORGANIZATION> Henkel </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Henkel </ORGANIZATION> said he still sees vestiges of the rancor that surrounded the project. `` But now, it's almost opposite to the earlier emotion of ` make the freeway as difficult as possible to get on and maybe they wo n't build it,''' he said `` Now they say, ` I live in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> and work on the Eastside and there's no way I can get on I-90 conveniently.'' <LOCATION> King </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> east of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has grown in the past two decades from small towns and farms to a suburban area of 360,000 people. Another 275,000 are expected by 2020, said <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, senior transportation planner for the <ORGANIZATION> Puget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sound </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governments </ORGANIZATION>. The county, which includes <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, has a population of about 1.4 million. Studies have shown the population of King and surrounding counties will grow by about 500,000 in the next decade.
