<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>'s, the venerable chain of ice cream parlors where the hot fudge sundae was invented, is trying to make a comeback under new ownership after a disastrous experiment in yuppie marketing. Last year, five of its seven stores closed, including the landmark location in <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Harvard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, where the mahogany paneling and marble table tops were ripped out for a pizzeria. The 116-year-old chain's former owner, <PERSON> Joey </PERSON> <PERSON> Crugnale </PERSON>, admits he goofed in trying to remake <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>'s as an upscale spot for people in their 20s and 30s. `` It was a mistake from the beginning,'' he said. `` But I'm not ashamed of it. I learned a lot from it.'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazzaferro </PERSON>, one of three brothers who bought the business in November for an undisclosed price, said he hopes to reopen stores in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION> within the next few years. `` I think the company lost its focus and it became more of a luncheon stop as opposed to an old-fashioned candy store and ice cream parlor,'' he said. `` We want to restore it to its roots.'' The <PERSON> Mazzaferro </PERSON> family, which has been making candy in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> since the 1950s, already is turning out <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>'s fudge at the rate of 20,000 pounds a year That would gladden the heart of <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Dow </PERSON>, the bookkeeper to founder <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>. When he retired in 1900, she became the shop's owner and took a gamble that made dessert history `` She put 6 ounces of ice cream in a 5-ounce dish and poured one and a half ounces of hot fudge on top of it, and it dripped down onto the silver dish,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyman </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a former <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>'s owner, sa