 Wages are down, work hours are up and vacations are out at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, which announced an austerity program designed to help the strike-crippled company rebuild from bankruptcy. Eastern said Friday it will eliminate vacations for the rest of the year, cut management pay by 20 percent and require non-union employees to work 50 hours a week for 40 hours of pay. Meanwhile, a judge in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> gave an investor group friendly with striking employees until Monday afternoon to refine a buyout proposal. The group is led by <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> commodities trader <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritchie </PERSON>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON>'s decree surprised observers who thought he would dismiss the <PERSON> Ritchie </PERSON> proposal as financially inadequate and vague. But <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shapiro </PERSON>, the court-appointed examiner for <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, told <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> he was impressed by a new version of the plan under which the unions would risk $ 175 million to $ 200 million of their wages over six months. Eastern sought protection from creditors under bankruptcy laws five days after pilots and flight attendants joined striking Machinists on March 4, reducing the airline's flights by more than 90 percent. The company plans to expand service and recall some 1,700 non-union employees by July 2. `` It's a unique situation. We're going to be the fastest-growing airline in history during the time we're going to be in bankruptcy,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON>, senior vice president for human resources. Under the austerity program, full-time agents and clerical workers will be scheduled to work 50 hours a week without a pay in