<SECOND>PM-Toronto Boom,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>With New SkyDome, is Canada's Largest City `Choking on Success?'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Dollar figures U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The new $ 355 million SkyDome stadium is the latest symbol of <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>'s rise to major league stature, but it has also led to questions about traffic congestion, crime and urban woes in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s largest city. Residents have poured civic pride into preparations for this evening's gala for the world's first stadium with a retractable roof. But many residents wonder how this fast-growing city can handle more downtown crowds. The concerns however go much further than downtown to address the quality of life throughout the booming metropolitan area, which has reached a population of nearly 4 million decades sooner than expected. `` We're really to some extent choking on our growth,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bossons </PERSON>, an economics professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> who long has been involved in municipal issues. `` We've been too successful in a sense.'' He recalled a transportation study of five or six years ago that projected a metropolitan population of 4 million by the year 2011. Five million people in metropolitan <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, which had half that many residents in 1971, now seems more appropriate for 2011. The 60,000-seat <LOCATION> Skydome </LOCATION>, at the foot of the landmark CN Tower, will be the home of the <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jays </ORGANIZATION> of baseball's <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Football </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Argonauts </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> Skydome </LOCATION> roof was designed to open or close in 20 minutes, but inspectors found exposed wiring, missing sprinklers and faulty fire prevention devices among 150 deficiencies. An operating permit finally was granted Thursday, but critics say deficiencies remain in the stadium, which they call another example of development run amuck. Critics also predict that fans will swamp already crowded streets and highways with the extra traffic to the complex. <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> has prided itself on keeping residential neighborhoods near downtown. Its public transit system still is considered a model. Movie set designers have to scatter garbage on the streets when trying to make <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> look like an American city. Not short on civic cheer, the city is seeking the 1996 Summer Olympics and a world's fair for the year 2000. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON>, director of the urban studies program at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION>, said residents are troubled at their recollections of a calmer, different <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> 10 or 15 years ago. `` It is n't that it's bad; it's just becoming a city,'' she said. Supporters of a movement that promises to firmly regulate development won a majority of city council seats in a municipal election late last year. `` It was very, very clear in the election that people were really concerned about what they perceive as a decline in the quality of life,'' <PERSON> Bosson </PERSON> said. `` We're a city at the crossroads,'' <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Layton </PERSON>, one of the most visible council members, said in an interview. `` I think the city has been a little too smug in thinking of itself as such a success.'' He said the housing problems in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> should be getting more attention than stadium-building. A newspaper poll of 1,800 people taken for a 10-part series in the <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> last month found that 35.6 percent of city residents were more afraid of walking alone at night than five years ago and 48 percent more afraid of riding the subway alone at night. `` We still brag that <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s largest city does n't have half the problems that are sucking the life out of urban <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' the series wrote. `` But suddenly we are n't so sure that it ca n't happen to us.'' Housing costs have soared in the economic boom that has lasted through most of the decade, pushing the average cost of a <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> home to more than $ 232,000 and making `` affordable housing'' a prime city issue. The only other Canadian city that even comes close is <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, where the average price has risen to $ 176,700. The average housing price in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> is $ 92,600 and in <LOCATION> Edmonton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alberta </LOCATION>, $ 71,600.
</TEXT>
