<FIRST>r a PM-Bush-Smog     06-03 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Smog,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Bush To Propose Alternative Fuels Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plans to press 25 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities to begin converting to alternative fuels as early as 1992 to battle urban smog, a newspaper reported today. The most stringent of the four options <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is considering would require that 50 percent of all new cars, trucks and buses in the 25 cities be required to run on alternative fuels by 1995, the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported. The least stringent option would require only buses and official automobiles in those cities to use alternative fuels, but would accelerate the deadline to 1992, the Times said. The cities were not identified in the 42-page White House document prepared by the President's <ORGANIZATION> Domestic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and obtained by the Times. But the cities would include <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> and other major urban areas, the Times said. The president's alternative fuels plan represents the central element of his effort to revive and overhaul the federal effort _ stalled under the <ORGANIZATION> Reagan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> _ to combat pollution in major cities. Alternative fuels, including compressed natural gas, methanol and ethanol, burn more cleanly than gasoline and reduce the production of ozone, the major component of smog. Even the stringent pollution-reduction plan outlined for the president would leave 23 cities in violation of federal air standards by the year 2005. Last summer, 81 cities fell short of the federal standards. The cost of the various proposals was not outlined in the document presented to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, but estimates range from $ 2.1 billion to $ 4.6 billion, the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said. The report says that the use of alternative fuels would `` obviate the need for other more costly automobile controls'' on emissions. Controls such as changes in tail pipes and fuel pumps have been strongly opposed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> auto makers. The report also suggests that cities be given the opportunity to `` opt out'' of the alternative fuels requirement if they can find other was to reduce smog substantially. The report was presented to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> before he left last weekend for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. It faces final review Monday during a meeting of the Domestic Policy Council.
</TEXT>
