<SECOND>PM-Seabrook Protest,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activists Gather for Big Anti-Seabrook Demonstrations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rally begins at noon EDT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEABROOK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Activists demonstrating this weekend at the <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> nuclear power plant say the imminent start of atomic testing at the reactor should help their cause. `` Now it's beginning to sound real. Before it was sounding kind of nebulous,'' <PERSON> Wes </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocheron </PERSON> of the anti-nuclear <ORGANIZATION> Clamshell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> said Friday night as the first demonstrators began trickling into this seacoast town. `` People are fired up against the nuke, especially now that they got the low-power testing license,'' <PERSON> Crocheron </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> gave <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> a low-power testing licence last week. The first atomic chain reaction is expected at the reactor by the middle of next week. The alliance was planning a major rally today at <LOCATION> Hampton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, on the crowded beach peninsula less than two miles from <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> that is a focal point of the struggle over whether the $ 6 billion reactor ever will operate commercially. Evacuation plans for the beaches and communities up to 10 miles away from the plant must be approved before the plant may operate commercially. On Sunday, the activists plan a mass civil disobedience action at the plant site. <PERSON> Clamshell </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON> said at least 300 to 500 people already had undergone non-violent civil disobedience training, and more training sessions were being held throughout the weekend. On Friday, <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> denied <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> town officials' request for an injunction against Sunday's demonstration <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> police Chief <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> indicated Friday police may arrest demonstrators before they reach the plant gates on Sunday. Some of the protesters hope to scale fences around the outer plant boundary and symbolically `` occupy'' the site. Protest organizers hope this weekend's demonstrations will be the largest in more than a decade at <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>. There have been about 2,500 arrests in protests that began when construction started in 1976, including 1,414 arrests in a May 1977 protest that helped make <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> a symbol of the nation's anti-nuclear movement.
</TEXT>
