<FIRST>r a PM-Transplants     06-03 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Transplants,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Organ Preservation Solution Revolutionizing Field</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Clinicians are preserving transplant organs for longer periods in an improved chemical solution that is healthier for patients and gives doctors more leeway in scheduling surgery. `` This solution is clearly better than what's been available. It's a major advance in transplantation,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, associate professor of surgery at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION>. The biggest impact has been in liver transplants, where half of all organs go to waste because of logistical and organizational problems, said the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION>'s Dr. <PERSON> Folkert </PERSON> <PERSON> Belzer </PERSON>, who developed the solution. His mixture, previously available to select transplant centers on an experimental basis, was approved for general use last month by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. The solution includes hormones, amino acids and sugars. It prevents tissue swelling and cell deterioration from the time the organ is removed from a brain-dead victim until it is transplanted. Under the older preservation method, livers were chilled and flushed with Euro-Collins solution, a mix of electrolytes and glucose. With the older solution, surgical teams had to spring into action as soon as donor organs were found and transplant candidates had to live near the center. Transplants often began in the middle of the night, with one operation sometimes starting as soon as another finished. Organs regularly were turned down because of a lack of doctors or surgical space. `` This is the first time we've ever been able to do a liver and pancreas electively,'' <PERSON> Belzer </PERSON> said Friday at the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surgeons </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> solution, called ViaSpan and marketed by <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON>, has allowed for greater sharing of organs. Last fall, for example, a liver was shipped from <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and successfully transplanted. Another was shipped from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. It's also enabled doctors to trim livers for young recipients or split them for two patients when necessary. Studies in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> have found livers can be preserved safely outside the body for as long as 36 hours with the solution, compared to a maximum six to eight hours with other methods, said Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Southard </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION>. Pancreases have been stored for as long as 29 hours with the solution, <PERSON> Southard </PERSON> said. The preservation time for kidneys remains about the same, 30 to 40 hours, regardless of which solution is used, <PERSON> Southard </PERSON> said. But studies show recipients of kidneys preserved in the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> mixture do not return as often to dialysis because of organ rejection and other problems.
</TEXT>
