<HEAD>Conservative Episcopalians Form Church Within Denomination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Conservative Episcopalians reacting to the election of the first woman bishop have created a new association to `` transform'' their denomination. Nearly 2,000 people attended the founding meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Synod </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> Friday. The delegates adopted a constitution Friday and planned to end their meeting today. The dissident church members said they were displeased with loosening strictures on marriage, tolerance of homosexuality, feminist theology, revisions of liturgical language to be gender-inclusive and what they saw as slackening standards of personal morality in the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. `` If we remain a church within the church, our goal is n't to be a small cell, but to be a witness to hopefully transform our religion,'' said Bishop <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Schofield </PERSON> of the Episcopal Diocese of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joaquin </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Fresno </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. But members of the new church say they do not intend to break with the nearly 2.5 million-member <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, which has lost about a quarter of its members since doctrinal controversies reached their peak in the mid-1970s. The church is one of 27 branches of the 70 million-member Anglican Communion worldwide. Bishop <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> was elected president of the new association. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s laws do not prevent the traditionalists from forming a voluntary association, and he called for the acceptance of the new organization as a way for traditionalists to stay within the church. Twenty-one other <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> bish