 A previously unknown Moslem group today claimed it planted a small bomb that exploded in front of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>. The homemade bomb, which caused no injuries, apparently was intended for the neighboring <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Police said it was hurled from a moving vehicle Friday after riot police fired tear gas and bullets to disperse 500 Moslem demonstrators trying to march to the <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Moslems accuse Indian peacekeeping troops of failing to prevent clashes between Tamils and Moslems in which at least 13 people were killed last month. Most Tamils are Hindu, and both groups are ethnic minorities among the majority Sinhalese Buddhists. Newspaper offices today received statements from the <ORGANIZATION> Noorul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> claiming responsibility for the bomb. Police said they have not heard of the group. Indian troops were sent to northern and eastern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> in 1987 to enforce a peace accord to end a Tamil separatist revolt. Moslems accuse the Tamils of trying to force them, as well as the Sinhalese, out of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION>. The province's population is equally divided among the three ethnic groups. Tamils account for 18 percent and Moslems 7 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people.
