<HEAD>Pope Calls For Reconciliation Of All Christians</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE pope arriving in Iceland, pleading for
reconciliation of Christians. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> pleaded for the reconciliation of all Christians on his arrival today in <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>, which has 1,800 Roman Catholics among its mainly Lutheran population of 244,000. Starting the second leg of a five-nation Scandinavian tour in one of the most unpolluted countries of the world, the pope also noted that people everywhere are beginning to recognize that the pursuit of materialism is threatening the environment. He also said people throughout the world are increasingly aware that peace among nations `` can only be the fruit of a just economic and social order.'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Steingrimur </PERSON> <PERSON> Hermannsson </PERSON> welcomed him at <LOCATION> Keflavik </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> on a gray and chilly day, saying the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> was received `` as a true servant of the God in whom we believe, regardless of the church to which we may belong.'' Christianity was established as the official church in <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION> 1,000 years ago, but <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholicism </ORGANIZATION> was vanquished by the <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reformation </ORGANIZATION> in the 16th century. The <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said part of this 24-hour visit to <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION> would `` seek to encourage the good relations which have developed between <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION> Catholics and the members of other ecclesial communities.'' `` Despite the tragic divisions which have long separated Christians, all of us must try to live in fidelity to the lord's will, to be instruments of his reconciliation, to maintain the unity of the spirit in the bond of peace. At the airport, the pope kissed the ground as soon as he stepped off his plane _ a gesture he makes in every country he visits for the first time. A crowd of youngsters waved Icelandic flags, and the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> kissed two young girls who presented him with flowers in the red, blue and white colors of <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>'s flag. The pope flew to this northernmost capital in the world, just below the <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Circle </LOCATION>, from <LOCATION> Tromsoe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, where he extolled marriage and strong family values in a country where many couples live together without getting married. Police took into custody four people as the pope celebrated Mass in the market square of <ORGANIZATION> Tromsoe </ORGANIZATION>, which is 200 miles north of the <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Circle </LOCATION>. Two women were detained for protesting closer relations with the Catholic church, and two men criticized the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s human rights record. Police estimated fewer than 1,000 people attended in one of the smallest crowds at an open-air Mass on the pope's 42 foreign trips. Speaking from a wooden altar, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> touched on an issue of concern to the churches in <LOCATION> Scandinavia </LOCATION>, where about 50 percent of the couples never marry and most children today are born out of wedlock. `` The love of a married couple unites them, but it also enables them to become cooperators with God in giving life to a new person,'' he said, speaking in English. `` Thus they establish the most basic of human communities, the family,'' which he said was `` a fundamental gift.'' Catholic officials have complained of the difficulty of encouraging traditional values in a secular atmosphere. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> also is visiting <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> on his 10-day tour. Only about 1 percent of Scandanavians are <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>. Lutheran churches are tax-financed and part of the state bureaucracy.
