<HEAD>Solidarity Candidates Stumping, Calling for Sweeping Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OJRZEN, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The smells of the land and hard-working men filled the room as farmers took time off from the fields to hear Solidarity's election pitch. The trio of candidates faced a stern crowd in this village 42 miles west of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, where cows graze almost to the edge of the pavement and horse-drawn wagons rumble down the narrow roads. Like some other rural areas, <PERSON> Ojrzen </PERSON> remains a pocket of support for the communist party. There are fewer than a half-dozen Solidarity posters, with their flowing red script that has become a trademark for the trade union born in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> nine years ago. In his campaign stop, Solidarity candidate <PERSON> Benedykt </PERSON> <PERSON> Pszczolkowski </PERSON> called for reforms ranging from better treatment of farmers to reductions in the bloated communist-led government. But, facing more than 70 farmers in the community center Friday, he was careful to avoid raising too many expectations in advance of Sunday's elections for the parliament and a new <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are n't making promises that the economy in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> will suddenly start to thrive,'' said the thin, bearded candidate, dressed in a natty sport coat at the end of a frenzied, two-month campaign. `` The people who control the farms do n't know the problems. For example, they're still buying machines that are too big for small operations,'' said the candidate, himself a farmer with 60 acres in the town of <LOCATION> Pszczolki </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gorne </LOCATION>, 18 miles away. <PERSON> Pszczolkowski </PERSON>, 38, is hitting emotional issues in a country where most farms remain in private hands, despite the communist system. He is well aware that party officials also have been making the rounds of hundreds of villages nationwide, promising to cure chronic shortages if they're given another chance to govern. Shortages in this country of 38 million people are a daily curse of life. They range from spare parts for tractors to food and vital parts for dental care. `` They are telling fairy tales,'' the Solidarity candidate said of the communist party candidates. Speaking from a makeshift podium of two tables pushed together and covered by an aging green satin cloth, <PERSON> Pszczolkowski </PERSON> said police should spend more time fighting crime than hunting down unauthorized newspapers. <PERSON> Stanislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Weglowski </PERSON>, 51, one of two other Solidarity candidates appearing at the campaign stop, called for legal and economic reforms. `` The factories are running at about 60 percent of their capacity, because there is a shortage of raw materials,'' said <PERSON> Weglowski </PERSON>, a parliament candidate. He also called for more housing, better education and public access to the state-dominated mass media. The candidates are bound to find that demanding sweeping reforms in virtually all aspects of public life is easier than implementing them. Solidarity chief <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> has reminded his supporters that plenty of `` hard work'' remains after Sunday's voting and the run-off elections on June 18. When <PERSON> Pszczolkowski </PERSON> and the other candidates finished their presentations, they opened the floor to questions. One farmer wanted to know whether it was true, as state-run radio reported, that only `` criminals and communist party rejects'' joined Solidarity. Another testily asked whether Solidarity is a union or a political party. A third man asked why the candidates failed to mention `` the working class.'' Another jumped up and said the questioner was a local official who gained office through the party system. Later, the Solidarity candidates headed nine miles down the road to their final stop, the village of <LOCATION> Sochocin </LOCATION>. About 150 farmers crowded into the community center to listen to the same speeches and pose many of the same questions as the farmers in <LOCATION> Ojrzen </LOCATION>. Communist party candidates have been keeping a much lower profile. `` Most people are for Solidarity,'' said retired farmer <PERSON> Sabina </PERSON> <PERSON> Walczewska </PERSON> as she sat in a wooden cart drawn by a tractor. `` Everyone here says with Solidarity things are going to change for the better _ maybe. Whether things really will be better, no one knows.'' The 73-year-old woman, her hands calloused from years on the land without modern machines, said she plans to vote for Solidarity.
