<HEAD>Car Thief Gets Stiff Sentence: 10,000 Sentences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLEASANTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When convicted car thief <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Loggins </PERSON> walked out of an <LOCATION> Alameda </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> courtroom, he had one sentence in jail and 10,000 more on paper. After <PERSON> Loggins </PERSON> pleaded guilty last year to car theft, Municipal Court Judge <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON> sentenced him to five weekends in the county jail and ordered him as part of his probation to write this sentence 10,000 times: `` If I do n't own it, I wo n't take it.'' This week, the judge ordered <PERSON> Loggins </PERSON>, 20, held without bail in the jail after he failed to complete the literary assignment, despite <PERSON> Loggins </PERSON>' sworn claim that he had completed 3,000 sentences. <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON> said nothing was produced for the court to see. He also ordered <PERSON> Loggins </PERSON> to return every day to the <ORGANIZATION> Livermore-Pleasanton-Dublin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> holding cell to complete his writing assignment. <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON> said that when he last checked Friday, <PERSON> Loggins </PERSON> had completed about 1,400 sentences. <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON> also said <PERSON> Loggins </PERSON> is taking his writing assignment `` in good spirits'' and will benefit from it. `` I want him to feel that this repetitive writing is about as foolish as what he did,'' <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON> said. `` I want people to know that if you steal, you're going to pay a price, and it is n't always jail.''
