<HEAD>FBI Sending Agent to Site of Crash That Killed Zia and U.S. Envoy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> is sending an agent to the site of the August plane crash that killed Pakistani President <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON> and <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Raphel </PERSON>, an agency official confirmed. The agent will be sent within a week, nearly 10 months after the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> was initially shut out of the investigation, said <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Revell </PERSON>, executive assistant director for investigations. The aim will be to seek evidence at the site where the plane went down Aug. 17, killing the two officials and 27 others, including Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wassom </PERSON>, the chief <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> defense representative to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s official report on the crash has been under review by the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> since October. It concludes that sabotage was the cause but does not pinpoint those responsible. <PERSON> Revell </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> has completed its review of the report. `` We have conducted all of our interviews of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> participants and witnesses and we are dispatching an agent to go on-scene to conduct an on-scene evaluation and we will go from there,'' he said. He said the decision to keep the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> out of the investigation appears to have come from within the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. `` The Pakistanis as we understand would have agreed for us to be there, but it was never presented to them,'' he said. `` I personally believe that this was a very unique situation, a very sensitive location with a U.s. ally teetering on the brink,'' <PERSON> Revell </PERS