<HEAD>Accountant's Arrest Helps Exorcise Town's 18-Year-Old Crime</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WESTFIELD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Eighteen years after authorities say <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> List </PERSON> methodically shot his family to death, people here see an end to the tale that has haunted this quiet, wealthy suburb. The former Sunday school teacher was arrested in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, last Thursday, where he had been living with a second wife of four years and working as an accountant. Nearly two decades of lead-chasing in every state, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> were terminated by a simple anonymous tip following a broadcast of the case on the television show `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Most Wanted.'' Police Chief <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Scutti </PERSON> said the murders left a black mark on the town of 32,000, 25 miles from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The arrest helped fade that mark. `` If they had a giant microphone in town, you would have heard a giant sigh of relief,'' <PERSON> Scutti </PERSON> said. When the chief went to an awards dinner the night of the arrest, he was greeted with a spontaneous standing ovation. `` I think that reflected the feeling of all of us,'' he said. On Dec. 7, 1971, police who had been alerted by worried neighbors found the bodies of List's wife and three children lying on sleeping bags on the ballroom floor of the family's 18-room mansion. Cloths covered the faces of <PERSON> Helen </PERSON>, 45; <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON>, 16; <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> 15; and <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON>, 13. The body of List's 85-year-old mother, <PERSON> Alma </PERSON>, was found in an upstairs closet. All five had been shot in the head. They apparently had been dead nearly a month. List, who had held jobs as an accountant and insurance salesman and was apparently beset by financial and family problems, had vanished. In many ways, the List case worked its way into the town's consciousness Teen-agers seeking excitement would cruise by the house, until it mysteriously burned down a year after the deaths. Almost every year, newspapers would run articles on the crime's anniversary And people remembered. <PERSON> Scutti </PERSON>, then a sergeant, recalled bringing <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> List </PERSON> to the stationhouse late one night several months before her death. She had slipped out the window and was going to meet a friend. `` Lo and behold, he comes in at 2:30 in the morning dressed in a business suit to pick up his daughter,'' <PERSON> Scutti </PERSON> said. List, <PERSON> Scutti </PERSON> said, sometimes dressed the same way to mow his lawn. <PERSON> Claudia </PERSON> <PERSON> Haller </PERSON> remembered being interviewed by List for a teaching job at the primary school connected with the Redeemer Lutheran Church. The red-brick, slate-roofed church, where List taught Sunday school, was just about the only community tie he had. Church was a constant: He used pastors as references for jobs and a gun permit three weeks before the crime. List met his second wife at a <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> church function in 1977, authorities said. `` I felt that he was a very intellectual man. He was just very calm and collected. You could see he was a very religious man, too,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Haller </PERSON> said. He was also a private man, given to eating lunch alone at work, said <ORGANIZATION> Westfield </ORGANIZATION> detective Lt. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON>. Now that one mystery _ List's whereabouts _ has been solved, another remains: why. List left letters, as yet undisclosed, to his pastor and others explaining his actions. List reportedly believed his family was falling away from their religion and had to be killed for their own good. A newspaper at the time included quotations from <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> List </PERSON>'s daughter by a previous husband who had died in the Korean War. Miss <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said the marriage with List was filled with tension because her mother was psychologically unstable and had a drinking problem. List's Lutheran pastor in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, during the early 1960s said more tension was created by Mrs. List's comparison of the meek List with her first husband, `` a strong military man.'' Toward the end, Mrs. List was bedridden for months and List's financial problems were mounting He was upset with his daughter's desire to become an actress and attachment to a young man considered in the `` wrong crowd,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Moran </PERSON>, police chief at the time The young man for several years left flowers at the family's grave in <LOCATION> Fairview </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cemetery </LOCATION>, where a single headstone records List's wife and `` I hope it ends for him more than it does for us,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Pletscher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Fanwood </LOCATION>, who was two years behind <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> in school. `` I hope he comes to grips with this whole thing.''
