<DATELINE>MYRTLE BEACH, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of people turned out to labor with shovels and bare hands for their moment of fame _ as builders of the world's longest sand sculpture. After crews worked much of the day under a hot June sun, a surveying company certified Friday that the sand castle measured 15,063 feet, giving the crew a good shot at getting into the next <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Book </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION>. The centerpiece of the project, a 15-foot-high castle with the logos of corporate sponsors, had been built earlier in the week by two leading sand sculptors, <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> <PERSON> Vander-Pluym </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Altamar </PERSON>. Then, volunteers made two long, long wings on the building Friday, following guide lines painted on the beach and taking care to sculpt the sand and not just pile it up. Festival chairman <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Snipes-Phillips </PERSON> said the surveyors' findings, along with videotape, photographs, and volunteers' signatures, will be sent to the Guinness Book of World The castle would appear to easily beat the 10,760-foot-long sand millipede built along <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Padre </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, in March 1987, which is listed in the 1989 Guinness book. Estimates of the number of folks manning the shovel brigades or otherwise helping on the project ranged up to 2,000. `` It's tough, but I think we'll make it,'' said one volunteer, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamb </PERSON>. The castle was called `` The Neverending Fantasy'' and included sculptings of a jet plane, a `` Jungle Lagoon Golf Course,'' a shark and a castle turret topped with a tiny cocktail umbrella. The project was part of the city's six-day Sun Fun Festival which opened on Friday. By Saturday, much of the castle remained, but the tide had already begun to wash away parts of it.
