 <PERSON> Stefan </PERSON> <PERSON> Szwarnowski </PERSON>, the oldest person to sail solo across the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>, is heading out to sea again. The 76-year-old Polish native left this <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> seashore community Friday to return home the same way he came, bound for <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> aboard the 24-foot Tawny Pipit. He has no radio transmitter and plans to navigate by sun and stars. At least one <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> friend has tried to talk him out of it and offered to buy him a plane ticket home. `` It -LRB- would be -RRB- a difficult trip for a 21-year-old man,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamann </PERSON>, a marina owner. In August, <PERSON> Szwarnowski </PERSON> showed up near <LOCATION> Townsends </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Inlet </LOCATION> after a 12-week voyage. His feat will land him in this year's <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Book </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> as the oldest person to sail alone across the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>, according to a spokesman for the book. During that trip, light winds doubled the time he thought it would take to make the crossing. His water supply ran low, and he lost weight. Since his arrival, though, he has regained some weight, traveled by train across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and made many friends, despite his broken English. <PERSON> Szwarnowski </PERSON> said he expects to arrive in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> in about six weeks. And what if he does n't arrive at all? `` If something happens, you're going,'' he said philosophically. `` If not, you're still going.''
