<HEAD>Sailor AWOL 20 Years a ``Dinsosaur,'' Leayer Pleads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sailor who went absent without leave during the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> War 20 years ago is a `` dinosaur'' from a different era, and should not be court-martialed, his attorney argued. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, who walked away from the <ORGANIZATION> Treasure </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> base and his wife and child in 1969, was tracked down by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> last month. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, 40, is charged with desertion and using marijuana. The drug charge was added because <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> tested positive for marijuana when he surrendered May 4, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials said. If court-martialed and convicted, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> faces up to seven years in prison. At a Friday hearing to determine whether <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> should be court-martialed or simply discharged, his attorney, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Nike </PERSON>, said, `` The man you see before you is sort of ... a dinosaur, someone from a different era.'' When <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> went AWOL from the base near here, he was 19, naive and angry that his wife had been unfaithful, <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Nike </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> remarried, fathered five children and became a respected foreman at a paint company. `` Basically, we do n't have the same person today that we had then,'' De <ORGANIZATION> Nike </ORGANIZATION> said, arguing that <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> should be granted the same discharge AWOL servicemen received under amnesty programs during the 1970s. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s prosecutor, <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, argued that <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s long absence without leave warranted strict punishment because it was `` aggravating.'' The presiding officer, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </