<BYLINE>By TERRY HUNT</BYLINE>
<HEAD>AP White House Correspondent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Saturday he deeply deplored the decision by the government of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to use force `` against peaceful demonstrators and the consequent loss of life.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, spending the weekend at his oceanside home before returning to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> after a week-long trip to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, issued a statement which condemned the Chinese tactics. `` It is clear that the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government has chosen to use force against <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> citizens who were making a peaceful statement in favor of democracy. I deeply deplore the decision to use force against peaceful demonstrators and the consequent loss of life,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Earlier, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had issued no formal reaction to the violence in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aides had said the administration's comments would be made by Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> was also sharply critical of the Chinese action. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s office later issued a statement in the president's own words `` We have been urging and continue to urge nonviolence, restraint and dialogue. Tragically, another course has been chosen. Again, I urge a return to non-violent means for dealing with the current situation.'' The president said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> had built a `` constructive relationship'' during the past 20 years through `` great efforts by both sides.'' The president added that the relationship had been beneficial to both nations. `` I hope that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will rapidly return to the path of political and economic reform and conditions of stability so that this relationship, so important to both our peoples can continue its growth.'' After returning from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on Friday, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> spent the day at their seaside estate with their daughter <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> and her children, <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ellie </PERSON>. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gates </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s deputy national security adviser and former deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>, was at <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s compound, providing updates of the developments in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. After an early morning jog, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spent a quiet day with no public appearances. He had endured a night of fitful sleep because of jetlag. He arranged a private afternoon meeting with <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> to brief him on the European trip, but neither planned any remarks afterward. The <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> Democrat has criticized <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as being too cautious and timid in dealing with initiatives from Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, but that was before the president won widespread praise for a new <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal to reduce <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and Soviet troops in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. European leaders hailed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as seizing the initiative from the Soviet leader. At a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> meeting that concluded last Tuesday, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also helped engineer a compromise to a dispute over <LOCATION> East-West </LOCATION> negotiations on short-range nuclear missiles. The agreement stipulates that no negotiations will be held until the signing of an agreement to reduce conventional forces and the reductions are already underway. Also plann