<HEAD>Guerrillas Kill Seven in Attack on Palace Guards</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE casualties, details; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leftist guerrillas bombed a bus carrying Government Palace guards through downtown Saturday, killing at least seven soldiers and police and wounding 24 other people, authorities said. A car blocked the bus while it was en route to the palace, police said. Two people maneuvered a pushcart loaded with explosives under the back of the bus then detonated the cargo, they said. The bus was carrying 42 people, mostly soldiers. Police said at least six soldiers and a policeman were killed in the bombing. They said at least 24 were wounded, including soldiers and bystanders. The guards let off a hail of gunfire but the suspects escaped, police said on condition of anonymity. The government of President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, who lives at the palace, is fighting two leftist guerrilla organizations, the Mao-inspired Shining Path and the pro-Cuban <ORGANIZATION> Tupac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amaru </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>. No group claimed responsibility for Saturday's attack.
