<HEAD>Jurors Must Decide What Congressman Knew About Money Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For jurors in the two-week-old perjury trial of former Republican Rep. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, a familiar question is taking shape: What did he know, and when did he know it? At issue is what <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> knew about money broker `` <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>'' _ actually undercover <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> Agent <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullaney </PERSON> _ and where <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> claimed he got his money. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> negotiated with the agent for $ 850,000 for home construction over one month in 1987. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> is accused in the 10-count indictment of lying to a federal grand jury in February 1988. Under the cloud of the indictment, he lost his bid for a third term to Democrat <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, onetime star of the `` Dukes of Hazzard'' television show, last November in a district in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s suburbs. If convicted, he faces 10 months to five years in prison on each count. The jury in the case has heard audio tapes and seen videotapes in which <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>, at various times, acknowledged that drugs were the likely source of the money `` Martinez'' had. In those conversations, <PERSON> Mullaney </PERSON> also told <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> that the deal involved `` washing'' of cash, and the congressman proposed receiving the money through a mortgage company created for the purpose by <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> associate <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> LeChasney </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> emigre who has since been convicted of money laundering. The tapes are the backbone of the government's case, as prosecutors try to prove that <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> lied when he testified he did not recall discussing the illegal nature of the money handling and that he did n't recall being told the money was narcotics money, among other allegations. <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>'s lead attorney, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendrix </PERSON>, says he will prove that <PERSON> LeChasney </PERSON> was `` psychotic liar'' who deceived <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> into thinking the deal for $ 850,000 from <PERSON> Mullaney </PERSON> was all right, while deceiving the agent into thinking <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> was a crook. In cross-examination over three days last week, <PERSON> Hendrix </PERSON> hammered at <PERSON> Mullaney </PERSON> over statements the agent himself made in the tapes. <PERSON> Mullaney </PERSON> told <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> at one point the money was `` flight capital,'' then said at another point that it was not and `` could be anything.'' Flight capital is money sent out of troubled areas by wealthy people seeking to invest or store it in a stable country like the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. And more than two dozen times, <PERSON> Hendrix </PERSON> forced <PERSON> Mullaney </PERSON> to concede that he did not know what kind of tale LeChasney was telling <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mullaney </PERSON>, the government's first witness in the case, was on the stand more than six days, going one-by-one over tapes of 16 conversations he had with LeChasney about the <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> deal, plus five with the congressman himself and two meetings with both men. Tapes the jury saw or heard include one of a meeting between the three on Sept. 13, 1987, at a posh <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> resort, `` Martinez'' told <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> `` clearly, I violate some currency laws,'' and `` my gut feeling is there has to be narcotics dollars in there. ... It is not flight capital.'' `` Anything you tell me is told in total confidence,'' <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> replied. Later, <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> said, `` I am basically using <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> as my buffer. ... What I have to say is, I borrowed money from <LOCATION> Gulfstates </LOCATION>,'' LeChasney's company. On Sept. 23, <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> indicated he knew LeChasney would handle the cash in circumvention of bank reporting laws. `` <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> is going to ensure that basically the money is funneled in a way so that there are no reports filed,'' <PERSON> Mullaney </PERSON> said. `` Yeah. I'm protected that way,'' <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> replied. Finally, as the deal collapsed on Sept. 26, <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> told the agent he would `` acknowledge'' an `` assignment'' of assets through LeChasney to <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, but he could not accept the cash directly, because `` I would then be laundering y' all's money. But <PERSON> Hendrix </PERSON>, in cross-examination, repeatedly asked <PERSON> Mullaney </PERSON> why he had misled the congressman when he told him flatly the money `` is flight capital.'' `` As opposed to being laundered out of some drug scheme,'' <PERSON> Swindall </PERSON> said. `` I would assume so,'' the agent replied. <PERSON> Mullaney </PERSON> testified that he was portraying a drug-money launderer, and such a person would fudge details of the deal when talking on the telephone.
