</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> <PERSON> Uplinger </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Verna </PERSON>, who produced and directed the Live Aid benefit for African relief in 1985, teamed up again for the telecast. The Swiss-based Centre for Our Common Future and Washington-based Uplinger Enterprises put it together. `` To hold this kind of event lays the foundation of public awareness,'' said <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindner </PERSON>, executive director of the center. `` You know and I know that political change comes not in and of itself but is greatly facilitated by an informed and motivated public.'' The budget was just under $ 2 million, which is being covered by corporate sponsors, <PERSON> Lindner </PERSON> said. All the entertainers donated their talents, as did many other professionals and technicians involved. Setting up the satellite links and other organizational tasks were similar to the Live Aid program, which was held in two outdoor sports stadiums in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, he said. The difference is in the participants. Live Aid was virtually all music and had Irish rock musician <PERSON> Geldof </PERSON> as its host. `` It's been a very, very difficult situation,'' <PERSON> Uplinger </PERSON> said. `` You have heads of state involved. You ca n't do the same things with Mrs. <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON> as you can do with <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Geldof </PERSON>.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON> chaired a U.N.-appointed commission that spent three years gathering testimony and information to compile a report on the world's environment and development. The report was also called `` Our Common Future.'' She received the 1988 Third World Prize from the London-based Third World Foundation for her work of the commission.
