<FIRST>r a AM-Koop-HealthCare     06-03 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Koop-Health Care,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koop Calls for `Profound Change' in American Health Care System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retiring Surgeon General <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> said Saturday the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> health care system is unfair to millions of Americans, and he called for the appointment of a presidential commission to draft a plan for change. In a commencement address to 2,200 graduates of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> catalogued the ills of the medical delivery and insurance system, laying particular emphasis on inequities. `` Our current system of health care is not fair, it's not just, and it's not the morally strong system this country deserves,'' he said. The 72-year-old <PERSON> Koop </PERSON>, who is retiring this year after eight years as surgeon general, cited estimates that 37 million Americans _ about 15 percent of the population _ have no health insurance, while millions of others have only partial coverage. He said health care costs have been rising at two to three times the rate of inflation as a whole, and public expectations of medical care are `` fast outracing our ability to pay for them.'' The former pediatric surgeon also was critical of both doctors and hospitals, saying he did not foresee `` the medical profession achieving any success in self-regulation.'' He noted that many hospitals have tried to cut the number of indigent patients they treat. `` I say there's something terribly wrong with a system of health care that spends more and more money to serve fewer and fewer people,'' he said. <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> provided no specific recommendations for reform, however, beyond suggesting the appointment of a presidential commission. He did not call for national health insurance, even though he was introduced by Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., a strong supporter of that concept He also steered clear of the term socialized medicine, saying he favored a `` laissez-faire marketplace and a competitive economy.'' One of the problems of the current health care system, he said, is that it is `` distinguished by a lack of competition in price, quality or service.'' `` We need a presidential commission, the bluest of blue-ribbon panels, to consider the future of health care in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> suggested that the panel include health care professionals, insurance industry representatives and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. While the creation of a more equitable health care system will be `` a major task for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> said, it is something `` we need to prove to ourselves and the world'' if the nation is to retain its moral strength.
