<HEAD>Activists Rally Against Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE that rally largest in 11 years,
include details, quotes; CORRECT that May 1977 protest was at Seabrook
site, sted at gates; picks up 9th graf, `Before the ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAMPTON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 4,000 anti-nuclear activists Saturday staged the biggest rally against the <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> nuclear plant in 11 years, a prelude to a civil disobedience protest planned for Sunday. Traffic lined a highway that runs by the seaside plant, and many of the cars sported anti-Seabrook signs. At <LOCATION> Hampton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, less than two miles from the plant, protesters heard speakers denounce <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> and promise to continue fighting to prevent it from operating commercially. <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> opponent <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Comley </PERSON> drew cheers when he told the gathering he had hired planes pulling anti-nuclear banners to fly over the beach Saturday and about 40 miles up the <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> coast to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s home at <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, on Sunday. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was spending the weekend there. `` The nuclear industry and some of the people in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> believe this fight is over,'' <PERSON> Comley </PERSON> said. `` I'll tell you, we're just starting. The anti-nuclear <ORGANIZATION> Clamshell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> is organizing the protests, which it hopes will be the biggest since May 1977, when 1,414 people were arrested at the <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> site. About 2,500 arrests have been made in protests at the plant since construction began in 1976. Saturday's rally had the largest turnout since a 1978 protest that drew an estimated 18,000 people. Officials in neighboring <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> also have sought to block the plant by refusing to cooperate with emergency evacuation planning. Despite the opposition, <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> won its low-power testing license from federal regulators on May 26, nearly three years after the $ 6 billion reactor was completed. Plant officials have begun preparing for the first atomic chain reaction by Tuesday or Wednesday, plant spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sher </PERSON>, who stopped by the rally, said the protesters represented a `` vocal minority.'' `` But the majority of people in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and the rest of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> recognize that nuclear power is a viable energy alternative and <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> ... is ready to produce electricity and it can make an important contribution,'' <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> said. The plant first must win federal approval for evacuation plans for crowded summer beaches and communities up to 10 miles away. `` The truth is you can not evacuate <LOCATION> Hampton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> and the other beaches and protect the people,'' attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Backus </PERSON>, who has represented anti-Seabrook groups since 1972, told the crowd. `` The truth is we do n't know what to do with nuclear waste,'' <PERSON> Backus </PERSON> said. `` The truth is that the plant is uneconomic.'' Before the weekend, at least 300 to 500 people went through training sessions on non-violent civil disobedience, <PERSON> Clamshell </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON> said. The sessions continued Saturday. On Sunday, some activists planned to climb fences surrounding the 715-acre plant site and others planned to sit down outside gates. Some protesters also planned to go to a railroad siding at the plant to re-create an August 1976 protest in which 18 people were arrested _ the first group civil disobedience against a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear power plant. Earlier in the week, <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> let the town charge the organizers a $ 300 fee and $ 3,600 bond for an assembly permit. Clamshell members said they could n't and would n't pay Since a town ordinance bars gatherings of more than 25 people without a permit, the activists said they planned to march to the plant on Sunday in groups of fewer than 20.
