<HEAD>Americans Think Ethics Craze Is Paralyzing Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Many Americans think the current focus on ethics is paralyzing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government, but about half said Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> was treated fairly by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>, according to a poll released Saturday. Fifty-four percent of the people interviewed said the attention to ethics was preventing the government from focusing on the budget deficit, education, crime, drugs and the homeless, according to the poll, which will be published in this week's Newsweek magazine. But 41 percent said it was necessary to restore integrity and confidence in government. On the controversial issue of congressional pay raises, 56 percent of Americans oppose any pay increase, the poll found. Fifteen percent said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should get a raise and 26 percent said members should get a raise only if they give up speaking fees, the poll said. Asked to describe <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' greatest problem, 53 percent said members were not dealing with the nation's real problems; 20 percent said they were too tied to special interests through campaign contributions; and 18 percent pointed to the sexual misconduct, excessive drinking and unethical financial dealings of members. Forty-nine percent said the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> gave fair treatment to <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, who announced his resignation last week after being cited for ethics violations. Twenty-eight percent said he was n't treated fairly and 23 percent said they did not know, according to the poll. Although 53 percent of the people surveyed said most or many members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> take unethical advantage of their positions to make outside income, 47 percent said their own representatives take no such an advantage. Thirty-one percent said they did and 22 percent did not know. The poll, conducted for <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Gallup </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, interviewed 750 adults by telephone Thursday and Friday. The margin of error was plus or minus 4 percentage points.
