<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leftist rebels on Saturday spurned the new rightist president's proposal for dialogue, dismissing it as a call to capitulate. The rejection came in a communique from the rebels' <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> broadcast on local radio stations. There was no immediate reaction from the government. Despite their rejection of the offer to talk, the guerrillas also said Saturday that they lifted a ban on road travel called to protest the inauguration Thursday of the President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> on Friday called for more regional efforts to end <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s civil war. He said bringing peace to this country was just as important as dismantling the U.S.-supported Nicaraguan rebels. He has pledged not to negotiate changes in the political system with the rebels but has offered talks instead on integrating them into civilian life. In their statement, the rebels said they stood ready to negotiate a political solution to their nine-year war against the U.S.-backed government. But they said <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>'s proposal did not offer them a chance to do so and that it was an `` invitation to surrender.'' The rebel communique instead invited <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s political parties to sponsor a peace dialogue. The rebels said the new president had been trying to project `` an image acceptable to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the European community, but the content of his speech was predominantly confrontation, strictly faithful to the politics and economics of Arena.'' Arena is <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>'s rightist <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>. The party takes a hard line on the war, and many observers expect the fighting to intensify under the Arena government. About 70,000 people, mostly civilians, have already died in the civil war. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> assumed power from President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>, a Christian Democrat. <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> is suffering from cancer and has left the country for more chemotherapy. The rebels' traffic ban had paralyzed nationwide traffic since Wednesday. `` All highways are reopened to the free circulation of vehicles,'' said the rebel <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Venceremos </ORGANIZATION> in Saturday's broadcast It said the rebels also ordered all guerrilla units `` to suspend any further action'' against motorists. Guerrillas damaged or destroyed five vehicles and dynamited power transformers and electrical transmission towers, but no injuries were reported. The country's 245 gas stations were also forced to remain closed for fear of rebel reprisals. Speaking at his news conference Friday, <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> reiterated accusations made by <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> that <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s ruling leftist Sandinista regime was helping the Salvadoran guerrillas. The Sandinistas have often denied such charges, claiming they provide only moral support. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> praised a Central American initiative aimed at negotiating peaceful solutions to conflicts in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. The accords call for demobilizing the Nicaraguan rebels, who now live in border camps in neighboring <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>.
