<HEAD>Violence at Tiananmen Could Leave Permanent Scar on China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Smoke from burning vehicles cast a pall over Tiananmen Square Sunday morning after violence that will leave a permanent scar on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The numbers of dead and wounded from military attacks on demonstrators were estimated in the hundreds. Massive arrests are inevitable along with purges in the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leadership. The military action made it clear the government was willing to use brutal force against mainly unarmed and peaceful demonstrators to ensure the privileges and power of an aging leadership and to perpetuate the political system. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s 84-year-old senior leader, may have forfeited his place as one of the 20th century's great statesmen _ his 10 years of economic reforms tarnished by his willingness to have blood shed rather than relinquish political power. Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON>, who refused to meet with students and discuss their pleas for greater democracy and instead declared martial law in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> on May 20, has won the odium of millions. Other elder leaders who dredged up their hard-line ideologies rather than listen to the pulse of the nation also will be known as men who sanctioned the killings of young idealists. The <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> betrayed the chants of the students that `` the people's army loves the people'' _ reflecting the respect many Chinese had for the army until Sunday morning. The crushing of the protests reaffirmed <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s philosophy that political stability is crucial for economic modernization and social unrest is intolerable. But his quest for stability may be in jeopardy. Military force will not quiet the resentment of official corruption expressed by the students at <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION>. Troops in the streets may drive anti-government and anti-party expressions underground for a while but they can not eradicate them. Student leaders, referring to government suppression, spoke of a `` long winter'' coming that will affect the nation's faltering economic plans. With the government divided and weakened by strife, problems of inflation, unemployment and labor unrest will be unattended. If the conservatives push through their purge of <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON> and other moderates who opposed the crackdown, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> could be deprived of a generation of creative and progressive thinkers. The flow of desperately needed foreign investments will suffer because of the political crisis. Tourism will decline. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, long at odds over human rights issues, could be heading for cooler relations that will involve <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> willingness to provide technology and economic assistance. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Saturday he deeply deplored the decision to use force `` against peaceful demonstrators and the consequent loss of life.'' Chinese leaders often note <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s 4,000-year history and say the Chinese have the wisdom and patience to outlast crises of the moment. But Chinese observing the rapid changes in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> will not be satisfied with reciting catechisms of communism and the evils of bourgeois liberalization. Chinese need only look back at the last Tiananmen Incident on April 5, 1976, to note that violence can destroy those who initiate it. On that date a radical clique seeking to cement its power ordered out military units that killed about 100 people who had gone to the square to mourn the late Premier <PERSON> Chou </PERSON> <PERSON> En-lai </PERSON>. Horror and anger at the killings led to events that brought about the downfall of the radicals six months later and the emergence of <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>.
