<HEAD>Jackson to Move to Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, considered a potential candidate for mayor of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said Saturday night that he intends to move into a home he owns in the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> once renovations are completed. But <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> that he had not made any decision on whether he make the capital his legal voting residence _ a move he would be required to make by November if he is to become a candiate for mayor in the city's 1990 elections. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> will probably move into the house in August or September, said a source close to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, speaking on condition of anonymity. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, a long-time <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> resident, purchased a home in the district four years ago, but it has remained vacant and in need of substantial repairs. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> began renovation work on the home this year. Asked if he intends to move into the home when the work is finished, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said, `` Of course, yes.'' Asked if he intends to make it his legal residence and to register to vote in the city, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> answered, `` we have not made such a decision.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has said repeatedly that he is in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> several times a week and he wants to live in the house rather than stay at a hotel. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> has the object of criminal investigations involving drugs and has been beset by a series of embarrassing disclosures about his personal life. A federal grand jury is investigating <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>'s repeated visits to the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> hotel room of a man, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, who was l