<HEAD>$20 Million Con Man Receives Stiff Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man convicted of bilking hundreds of people of $ 20 million through a pyramid scheme received a 15-year prison sentence with an unusual 10-year probation, but promised investors they'd get their money back. Authorities, however, said the reimbursement plan that <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> proposed Friday was just another attempt to mislead investors in his SH Oil and Gas Exploration company. Circuit Judge <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Strickland </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Bartow </LOCATION> sentenced <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> on Wednesday to 15 years in prison, and banned him from owning an expensive home, driving an exotic automobile or doing consulting work for 10 years after his release. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, 38, will also be prohibited from making more than $ 30,000 a year during the probation, and must give lectures on the evils of white-collar crime at colleges and high schools. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, who has also been sentenced to 10 years behind bars on federal bank fraud violations, could be released from prison after four years. His attorney, <PERSON> Montjoy </PERSON> <PERSON> Trimble </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, said he would appeal <PERSON> Strickland </PERSON>'s probation sentence. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> pleaded guilty in March to 98 state felony charges. He was accused of cheating about 700 investors out of $ 20 million between 1979 and 1987 through a $ 125 million pyramid scheme. A creditors meeting at bankruptcy court in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> on Friday marked the first time that <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> answered questions from both investors and investigators since the state closed SH Oil in December 1987. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> promised 50 investors who attended that he would provide a reimbursement plan to `` handle any and all alleged shortfalls you've had since SH Oil was closed.'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> did n't elaborate on the plan during the meeting, but said it was designed to refund lost investments within 10 to 15 years. He said the plan would pay investors $ 1 to $ 1.5 million annually for nine to 14 years, then pay them a lump sum of $ 11.5 million to $ 18 million in 10th or 15th year. Attorney <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>, hired to help <ORGANIZATION> SH </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION>'s federal trustee, called <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s plan `` Ouija board'' economics. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, the trustee administering $ 10 million to $ 15 million worth of seized SH Oil assets, said the reimbursement plan is `` taking assets and playing investment games with them.'' `` I say just give the money back to creditors and let them manage their own money,'' <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy Feb. 24. He claimed assets of about $ 15 million and liabilities of about $ 250 million. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, who remains free on $ 350,000 in state and federal bonds, is scheduled to report to <LOCATION> Saufley </LOCATION> federal prison near <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION> on Wednesday, his attorney said.
