<HEAD>Health Workers Say Prostitution and Prejudice Hindering AIDS Efforts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Aids, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prostitution and prejudice against homosexuals are hindering efforts to control the spread of AIDS in developing countries, a group of international health workers said Saturday. They spoke in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> Fifth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> on AIDS opens Sunday and 12,000 delegates are expected to attend. Prostitution has been a major factor in the `` wildfire-like spread of AIDS through <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Chandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Mouli </PERSON>, head of an AIDS education project in <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>. `` Because of high levels of unemployment ... young women often have no practical alternatives to prostitution.'' <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> has received reports of 23,000 cases of AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> but many cases are not reported and the figure is believed to be closer to 100,000. Poverty also has contributed to the large numbers of male prostitutes in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Natee </PERSON> <PERSON> Teerarojjanapongs </PERSON>, a Thai specialist. He said there have been few attempts to educate <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>'s homosexuals and test them for the presence of the virus of the deadly disease <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaminsky </PERSON>, a Costa Rican community health worker, said that in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> countries most AIDS victims have been homosexual men and hemophiliacs. Central and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> countries have reported 11,000 AIDS cases to the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. The number of AIDS victims in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is nearing 100,000. Ms. <PERSON> Kaminsky </PERSON> said poor relations between police and Latin American homosexual communities have hampered the detection and prevention of AIDS. `` Lack of trust in the authorities has been a major obstacle,'' she said. `` Homosexuality has been repressed by the police, gay bars have been closed and gays have been pursued.'' A government-sponsored television campaign in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> to educate the public about AIDS encountered strong social opposition, said <PERSON> Alonso </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Carrera </PERSON>, a Santiago-based health worker. When the messages were broadcast in March following long delays, they were aimed exclusively at the heterosexual population and contained no concrete information on prevention of AIDS, he said. African governments are struggling to control the AIDS epidemic, the health workers from that continent said. A study in the <LOCATION> Kagera </LOCATION> region of northwestern <LOCATION> Tanzania </LOCATION> found 4,000 orphans were AIDS carriers, said Dr. <PERSON> F.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Owenya </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> worker. He said that in addition to prostitution in the region, the common practice of sharing of unsterilized instruments such as razor blades and safety pins to pierce ears has contributed to the spread of AIDS.
