graf, The Rev. ... with minor editing; ADDS 6 grafs details, background.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gunmen killed a Roman Catholic priest, two policemen and four civilians in separate attacks, and police said Friday they increased security for <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s police chief after learning he is on a drug cartel's assassination list. Also Friday, leftist guerrillas freed four engineers of the Brazilian state oil company <ORGANIZATION> Petrobras </ORGANIZATION> who were kidnapped in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and held 43 days in the tropical interior, a company official said. The Rev. <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Restrepo </PERSON> was killed Thursday by unidentified gunmen near <LOCATION> Tierralta </LOCATION>, about 280 miles north of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> in an area where guerrillas are active, authorities said. Police had no motive for the slaying. Late Thursday, in the western city of <LOCATION> Pereira </LOCATION>, armed men entered a restaurant and sprayed it with gunfire, killing two men and two women and wounding six people, police said. <PERSON> Pereira </PERSON> is capital of the coffee-growing state of <LOCATION> Risarlda </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Risarlda </PERSON>'s governor, <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Patino </PERSON>, and two aides left the restaurant minutes before the attack, but police said the attack apparently was not directed at them. Early Friday, two policemen were shot to death near <LOCATION> Anoril </LOCATION>, about 200 miles north of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, in an apparent guerrilla ambush. Meanwhile, authorities in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> said they were strengthening security for the national police chief, Gen. <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> <PERSON> Padilla </PERSON>, and Gen. <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Munoz </PERSON>, chief of the police force's anti-narcotics division, after discovering they were on an assassination list of the feared <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> cartel of cocaine traffickers. The existence of the list was disclosed by <PERSON> Padilla