<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Nomads Adv07   06-03 0808</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Nomads, Adv 07,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed AMs, June 7 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>``Nomads: Masters of the Eurasian Steppe.'' Exhibit Provides Glimpse
of Cultural Side of Nomads</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDY SHORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Germans thought the diminutive horse soldiers with Oriental features were devils when they first invaded <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in the 5th century with <PERSON> Attila </PERSON> <PERSON> the </PERSON> <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> at their head. Nine centuries later, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> recoiled in horror as another Eurasian horde led by <LOCATION> Tamerlane </LOCATION> razed cities and stacked human skulls into towering pyramids. The Chinese even built The Great Wall of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in the 3rd century to keep out the havoc-wreaking warriors. But scholars say the Eurasian nomads were not the simple barbarians history often has portrayed them as. Situated along key trade routes linking <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the nomadic tribes had a class system and customs, and invented saddles, the game of polo and bow-stringed instruments. `` They created their own culture in spite of being viewed as barbarians by the sedentary population,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Basilov </PERSON>, chief curator of the Soviet exhibit, `` NOMADS: Masters of the Eurasian Steppe,'' which opened June 4 at the Denver Museum of Natural History. `` We should n't think that they just rode with their animals _ dirty and joyful with their food. Again, they created their own culture.'' The exhibit, which covers a 3,000-year span of the nomadic culture, represents the largest cultural exchange in the field of natural history between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> Featuring nearly 1,400 artifacts, the exhibit began its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tour in February at the Natural History Museum of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. It will remain in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> through Sept. 10, and will make its final stop at the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The exhibit also has been shown in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The artifacts were collected from eight museums across the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and include some that never have been displayed in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, museum officials said. <PERSON> Basilov </PERSON>, who has worked on the project for about 10 years, said the three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sites were chosen because they were large enough to accommodate the exhibit's size. From mannequins modeling brilliantly colored clothing to a tiny bronze lock molded in the shape of a deer, the exhibit provides an unusual glimpse into the nomadic culture. Among the artifacts is a full-size suit of golden armor, complete with headdress that was uncovered in the tomb of a warrior. There are examples of weaponry; cooking and eating utensils carved from wood and gourds, and small wooden trunks. The yurt, a rounded tent-like structure with a wool covering to keep out the rain, provides a look at the nomadic home life. Inside, the tent is divided for men and women in the traditional setup. Delicate, carved jewelry and a silver-and-gilt saddle arch and other ornaments also are in the display. Roaming along the Eurasian Steppe, a grassland area ranging from northern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the nomadic tribes thrived from 800 B.C. into the early 20th century. Some of the well-known leaders were <PERSON> Attila </PERSON> the Hun, and <PERSON> Kublai </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Tamerlane </LOCATION>, descendants of <PERSON> Genghis </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>. The tribes moved animal herds from pasture to pasture, and traveled along the <LOCATION> Silk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION>, a major trade route used to transport silk and other goods from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. Museum officials said the nomads have been credited with helping develop economic trade, and sharing ideas on religion, art and technology. `` They invented their own dwellings that could be transported from one place to another,'' <PERSON> Basilov </PERSON> said. `` They thought about the possibility to make everything they possess light, not heavy, not breakable, so convenient to their way of life.'' Among their inventions were the trousers, saddles and harnesses for horses and bow-stringed instruments, the curator said. Although there still are nomads living in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and parts of <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Basilov </PERSON> said they have settled into a more sedentary lifestyle, such as sheepherders moving their flocks between permanent dwellings. But, the way of life still has `` the flavor of their own essence of culture. Some elders that live today remember that in their youth they had this way of life,'' he said. <PERSON> Basilov </PERSON> received his doctorate in anthropology from the <ORGANIZATION> Mikloukho-Maclay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethnography </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, part of the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. He has held several positions, including senior researcher and scientific secretary at the institute. Currently, he heads the institute's <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION> Research. He believes the exhibit is unique because its message is that the nomads were not just barbaric tribes. Although <PERSON> Basilov </PERSON> has worked on the project for more than a decade, it still fascinates him: `` The more you work, the more interest you have in different fields of this very interesting culture.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, June 7</NOTE>
